      <h1>Roti Making Machine Price in India 2026: Complete Buyer's Guide</h1>
      <div class="article-meta">
        <span>📅 Updated: March 2026</span>
        <span>⏱️ 12 min read</span>
        <span>🇮🇳 India-focused pricing</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Roti making machine prices in India in 2026 range from ₹15,000 for a basic manual roti press to ₹8 lakh or more for a fully automatic commercial roti machine capable of making 1,000+ rotis per hour.</strong> With India's food service industry booming — from dhabas to five-star hotels, cloud kitchens to school canteens — the demand for efficient, consistent roti production has never been higher. This guide covers everything you need to know before buying a commercial roti making machine in India.</p>

    <h2>Types of Roti Making Machines in India</h2>
    <p>Roti making machines come in three main types, each suited to different production volumes and budgets:</p>

    <h3>1. Manual Roti Press (Chapati Press)</h3>
    <p>The simplest type — a heavy cast iron or stainless steel press that flattens pre-portioned dough balls into round rotis. No electricity required. The operator feeds dough balls by hand and presses them flat. Then each roti is cooked on a separate tawa or tandoor.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹3,000 – ₹15,000</li>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 100–200 rotis per hour (operator-dependent)</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Small dhabas, home caterers, small canteens</li>
      <li><strong>Advantage:</strong> No electricity, low maintenance, very affordable</li>
      <li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> Still labour-intensive, inconsistent size/thickness</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2. Semi-Automatic Roti Machine</h3>
    <p>A semi-automatic machine handles the pressing and cooking process with minimal operator intervention. The operator loads dough balls; the machine presses them and in some models feeds them to a cooking conveyor. Some models include an integrated gas-fired conveyor belt that cooks the roti as it travels.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹45,000 – ₹2,50,000</li>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 300–600 rotis per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Medium-sized restaurants, canteens, QSR chains</li>
      <li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Good balance of automation and cost</li>
      <li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> Still requires an operator to feed dough</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Fully Automatic Roti Making Machine</h3>
    <p>The fully automatic roti machine handles everything from dough portioning to pressing, cooking (on a gas-fired conveyor), and in some models, stacking. These are high-capacity industrial machines used in large restaurants, hotel chains, airlines, and industrial canteens.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹2,50,000 – ₹8,00,000+</li>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 600–2,000+ rotis per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Large canteens, hotel chains, industrial kitchens, airline catering</li>
      <li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Maximum output, consistent quality, minimal labour</li>
      <li><strong>Disadvantage:</strong> High upfront cost, requires regular maintenance</li>
    </ul>

