    <h2>Key Factors to Consider When Buying a Roti Making Machine</h2>

    <h3>1. Required Output (Rotis Per Hour)</h3>
    <p>This is the most critical factor. Calculate your peak demand: if your restaurant serves 200 covers at lunch and each cover gets 3 rotis, you need 600 rotis in 2 hours — that's 300 rotis per hour at peak. Add 20% buffer for safety. So you'd need a machine capable of 360 rotis per hour.</p>

    <h3>2. Roti Size and Thickness</h3>
    <p>Standard roti diameter is 6–8 inches. Most commercial machines can be adjusted for size within a range. Check the minimum and maximum diameter settings. If you need very thin rotis or very thick parathas, not all machines can handle the full range.</p>

    <h3>3. Dough Compatibility</h3>
    <p>Most roti machines handle standard wheat flour dough. However, if you're making multi-grain rotis, millet rotis (jowar, bajra, ragi), or phulkas, not all machines are compatible. Check with the supplier before buying.</p>

    <h3>4. Gas vs Electric</h3>
    <p>The cooking section of most commercial roti machines uses gas (LPG or PNG) because it provides the high heat needed to puff rotis properly. The motor for pressing and conveying is typically electric. Ensure you have both gas and electrical connections in your kitchen before purchasing.</p>

    <h3>5. Footprint and Installation Requirements</h3>
    <p>Fully automatic roti machines are large — a mid-range model can be 6–10 feet long and requires ventilation. Measure your kitchen carefully. Also check the required gas pressure and electrical load (most require 3-phase power).</p>

    <h3>6. After-Sales Service</h3>
    <p>A roti machine is a critical production piece of equipment. If it breaks down during peak service, you're in trouble. Always choose a brand with a service centre in your city or a quick response time. Ask about spare parts availability and typical repair turnaround time.</p>

    <h2>Top Roti Making Machine Brands in India</h2>

    <h3>Vijay Industries</h3>
    <p>One of the most respected Indian manufacturers of roti making equipment. Based in Ahmedabad, with machines ranging from manual presses to fully automatic industrial models. Good after-sales service network across India. Price range: ₹50,000 – ₹5,00,000.</p>

    <h3>Multichef</h3>
    <p>Popular brand for semi-automatic and fully automatic roti machines. Known for reliability and good service network. Widely used in hotel chains and large canteens. Price range: ₹1,00,000 – ₹6,00,000.</p>

    <h3>Rotimatic (Smart Kitchen / Zimplistic)</h3>
    <p>The Rotimatic is a robotic roti-making machine designed for homes and small kitchens. It makes rotis fully automatically with minimal intervention. However, at ₹75,000–₹1,00,000+, it's expensive for its capacity (1 roti per 90 seconds) and better suited for home use than commercial production.</p>

    <h3>VMI (France) and Tortilla King (US)</h3>
    <p>Premium imported brands used in industrial settings. Prices are significantly higher (₹8L+) but build quality and reliability are exceptional. Used in airline catering and large institutional kitchens.</p>

    <h2>Roti Machine vs Manual Roti Making: When Does a Machine Pay Off?</h2>
    <p>A fully automatic roti machine at ₹3,50,000 makes financial sense when:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>You're producing 500+ rotis per day consistently</li>
      <li>Labour cost for a skilled roti maker is ₹15,000–₹25,000/month</li>
      <li>The machine replaces 2 roti makers, saving ₹30,000–₹50,000/month in wages</li>
      <li>At ₹40,000 monthly labour savings, payback period is under 9 months</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For smaller operations (under 300 rotis/day), a manual press plus a skilled roti maker may be more economical. Do the math for your specific operation.</p>

